Transcript

9. An Introduction to the 12 Essential Principles

[00:00:00]

All right, what is going on crafters? It is time for us to dive into the 12 Essential Principles. It's the moment you've been waiting for. I want to tell you a quick little tale here about a woodworker who was so focused on learning the tools of the trade, he never took the time to learn the fundamentals such as the right types of wood for the job.

He could use a plane, he could saw, drill, but when it came time to build a mere table, he had no idea

so why am I telling you this tale? The reason why I'm telling you the tale is because tools, techniques, and patterns are important, yes, but principles, thinking tools upon which you can orient yourself, these things are foundational.

And that's why we have 12 essential principles that are going to piece together.

The four pillars of scalable software development in a more manageable way

and this will be the way that we could venture into developing the skills that actually matter as a software developer.

So in this video, what we're going to do is we're going to [00:01:00] cover what the 12 essentials are and discuss why we need them.

Then I'll explain the three categories of essentials and then following that throughout the rest of this section We are going to do an overview of each of the 12 essentials We're gonna discuss how we're gonna learn each of them throughout the course.

So first of all?

What are the 12 essentials and why do we need them? You should know this by now. The reason we need these 12 essentials is because it's very hard to piece together and understand the four pillars. So we do need to go a little bit deeper in order to get close to actual practice.

And one thing that's important to note is that there's two types of knowledge. There is Sophia, which is the love of knowledge philosophy, and there is Phronesis, which is wisdom or mastery.

And having spent a ton of time going through the books and studying the experts, what I call, Phronomous developers, the masterful developers, I found that looking to them for guidance has helped me identify down what these principles are, and now I'm going to show them to you.

So there's three categories of essentials, the first being the metaphysical [00:02:00] category.

These two here are abstraction and the feedback loop, and these are based on the core mental models, and come closely from this idea of systems thinking.

If you'll remember, systems thinking is just a way for us to decompose problems in a way such that we can work through them in a systematic way. And the world is a patchwork of systems that are input output systems to each other. And that's what the metaphysical essentials are the core foundational pillar essentials because these are just basically the way the world works.

The theoretical essentials are the ones that have to do with everything that happens before we write code.

So this has to do with planning, getting very clear on who we're helping, how we're helping them, what are the capabilities, what are the features, what are the use cases, what are the concrete examples.

And then finally, when we're ready to actually implement things, we move over into the physical and this is the actual space. This is where we're actually writing hard source code and we're actually [00:03:00] implementing the features that we set out to build.

For example, we have techniques like composition and vertical slicing, which are very physical essentials.

And on the flip side, we have things like value identification and domain discovery, which are more theoretical essentials.

Now what to focus on in this section.

Again, think of this like planting seeds. It's going to be a little bit more high level for you.

I will try to ground this in examples so that you can get the gist of these. But do not fret because we are going to be using these essentials and refining them over time in the phases of craftship.

Let these begin to frame the way you look at code and frame the way you ascertain whether you are going down the right path or the wrong path.

So with that being said, let's go ahead and jump into the first essential and that is going to be abstraction.
